After this lesson you should be able to:

interpret slope as constant rate of change;
construct a line from slope-intercept form, point-slope form, or two points;
identify linear model parameters in context;
move among standard, factored, and vertex forms of a quadratic;
use the discriminant to predict the number and type of real roots;
read roots, intercepts, vertex, and axis of symmetry from a quadratic graph.

After this lesson you should be able to:

distinguish expressions, equations, identities, contradictions, and solution sets;
evaluate expressions by substitution while tracking the order of operations;
recognize when two expressions are equivalent;
expand, factor, collect, and simplify basic algebraic expressions;
solve one-variable linear equations and check solutions;
use SymPy to verify algebraic work without replacing mathematical reasoning.

After this lesson you should be able to:

explain a function as a rule that assigns each input exactly one output;
translate among formulas, tables, graphs, and verbal descriptions;
identify domain, range, intercepts, and zeros;
compute and interpret average rate of change;
use a graph to understand how changing inputs changes outputs;
recognize common families of functions by shape.

After this lesson you should be able to:

identify degree, leading coefficient, terms, and constant term;
expand, factor, and divide polynomial expressions;
connect roots, factors, and x-intercepts;
interpret root multiplicity from a graph;
predict end behavior from degree and leading coefficient;
use SymPy helpers to summarize and visualize polynomial structure.

Motivation
Polynomials are algebra’s most flexible elementary functions. They are built from powers of x, but they can approximate complicated functions, model smooth curves, and support numerical methods.
In advanced math, polynomials appear in:

Taylor approximations in calculus;
characteristic polynomials in linear algebra;
regression and interpolation in statistics/numerical methods;
optimization models and local approximations.

Reading the picture
In the plot:

the black segment is the radius of the unit circle;
the red segment shows the cosine component;
the blue segment shows the sine component.

Because every point is on a circle of radius 1, sine and cosine always stay between -1 and 1.

Interactive unit circle
Use the slider or type an angle between -360 and 360 degrees. Positive angles rotate counterclockwise; negative angles rotate clockwise.

unitCircleExplorer()







function unitCircleExplorer() {
  const root = html`&lt;section class="trig-explorer"&gt;&lt;/section&gt;`;
  const slider = html`&lt;input class="trig-angle-slider" type="range" min="-360" max="360" step="1" value="45"&gt;`;
  const input = html`&lt;input class="trig-angle-input" type="number" min="-360" max="360" step="1" value="45"&gt;`;
  const chart = html`&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;`;
  const values = html`&lt;div class="trig-values"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;`;

  const controls = html`&lt;div class="trig-controls"&gt;
    &lt;label&gt;
      &lt;span&gt;Angle&lt;/span&gt;
      ${slider}
    &lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;label&gt;
      &lt;span&gt;Degrees&lt;/span&gt;
      ${input}
    &lt;/label&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;`;

  slider.addEventListener("input", () =&gt; {
    input.value = slider.value;
    render();
  });

  input.addEventListener("input", () =&gt; {
    const angle = clamp(Number(input.value) || 0, -360, 360);
    input.value = angle;
    slider.value = angle;
    render();
  });

  root.append(controls, chart, values);
  render();
  return root;

  function render() {
    const angle = Number(slider.value);
    chart.innerHTML = "";
    chart.append(drawUnitCircle(angle));

    const radians = angle * Math.PI / 180;
    const cosine = Math.cos(radians);
    const sine = Math.sin(radians);

    values.innerHTML = `
      &lt;span&gt;cos(${angle}°) = ${cosine.toFixed(3)}&lt;/span&gt;
      &lt;span&gt;sin(${angle}°) = ${sine.toFixed(3)}&lt;/span&gt;
    `;
  }
}







function drawUnitCircle(angleDegrees) {
  const width = 560;
  const height = 560;
  const margin = 44;
  const radius = 210;
  const center = { x: width / 2, y: height / 2 };
  const radians = angleDegrees * Math.PI / 180;
  const point = {
    x: center.x + radius * Math.cos(radians),
    y: center.y - radius * Math.sin(radians)
  };
  const projection = { x: point.x, y: center.y };
  const radiusLabel = {
    x: (center.x + point.x) / 2 + 10,
    y: (center.y + point.y) / 2 - 10
  };
  const cosineLabel = {
    x: (center.x + projection.x) / 2,
    y: center.y + 28
  };
  const sineLabel = {
    x: projection.x + (projection.x &gt;= center.x ? 12 : -12),
    y: (projection.y + point.y) / 2
  };

  const svg = d3.create("svg")
    .attr("viewBox", [0, 0, width, height])
    .attr("role", "img")
    .attr("aria-label", "Interactive unit circle showing sine and cosine")
    .attr("class", "trig-unit-circle");

  svg.append("circle")
    .attr("cx", center.x)
    .attr("cy", center.y)
    .attr("r", radius)
    .attr("fill", "none")
    .attr("stroke", "#9aa0a6")
    .attr("stroke-width", 2)
    .attr("stroke-dasharray", "7 7");

  svg.append("line")
    .attr("x1", margin)
    .attr("y1", center.y)
    .attr("x2", width - margin)
    .attr("y2", center.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-axis");

  svg.append("line")
    .attr("x1", center.x)
    .attr("y1", margin)
    .attr("x2", center.x)
    .attr("y2", height - margin)
    .attr("class", "trig-axis");

  svg.append("line")
    .attr("x1", center.x)
    .attr("y1", center.y)
    .attr("x2", point.x)
    .attr("y2", point.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-radius");

  svg.append("text")
    .attr("x", radiusLabel.x)
    .attr("y", radiusLabel.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-label radius-label")
    .text("radius");

  svg.append("line")
    .attr("x1", center.x)
    .attr("y1", center.y)
    .attr("x2", projection.x)
    .attr("y2", projection.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-cosine");

  svg.append("text")
    .attr("x", cosineLabel.x)
    .attr("y", cosineLabel.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-label cosine-label")
    .attr("text-anchor", "middle")
    .text("cosine");

  svg.append("line")
    .attr("x1", projection.x)
    .attr("y1", projection.y)
    .attr("x2", point.x)
    .attr("y2", point.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-sine");

  svg.append("text")
    .attr("x", sineLabel.x)
    .attr("y", sineLabel.y)
    .attr("class", "trig-label sine-label")
    .attr("dominant-baseline", "middle")
    .attr("text-anchor", projection.x &gt;= center.x ? "start" : "end")
    .text("sine");

  svg.append("circle")
    .attr("cx", point.x)
    .attr("cy", point.y)
    .attr("r", 6)
    .attr("class", "trig-point");

  svg.append("text")
    .attr("x", width - margin + 8)
    .attr("y", center.y + 5)
    .text("x");

  svg.append("text")
    .attr("x", center.x + 8)
    .attr("y", margin - 12)
    .text("y");

  return svg.node();
}

function clamp(value, min, max) {
  return Math.max(min, Math.min(max, value));
}

After this lesson you should be able to:

solve linear inequalities and compound inequalities;
write solution sets using interval notation;
explain why multiplying an inequality by a negative number reverses the sign;
interpret absolute value as distance;
solve absolute value equations and inequalities;
identify basic domain restrictions from denominators and radicals.

Guess the expression
Choose the expression that matches the graph.

quiz = quizApp()







function quizApp() {
  const root = html`&lt;section class="quiz-shell"&gt;&lt;/section&gt;`;
  const state = {
    total: 5,
    index: 0,
    score: 0,
    question: null,
    answered: false
  };

  renderStart();
  return root;

  function renderStart() {
    root.innerHTML = "";

    const input = html`&lt;input class="quiz-count" type="number" min="1" max="100" value="${state.total}"&gt;`;
    const button = html`&lt;button type="button"&gt;Start quiz&lt;/button&gt;`;
    const controls = html`&lt;div class="quiz-start"&gt;
      &lt;label&gt;
        &lt;span&gt;Number of questions&lt;/span&gt;
        ${input}
      &lt;/label&gt;
      ${button}
    &lt;/div&gt;`;

    button.addEventListener("click", () =&gt; {
      state.total = Math.max(1, Math.min(100, Number(input.value) || 5));
      state.index = 0;
      state.score = 0;
      startQuestion();
    });

    root.append(controls);
  }

  function startQuestion() {
    state.question = makeQuestion();
    state.answered = false;
    renderQuestion();
  }

  function renderQuestion() {
    const question = state.question;
    root.innerHTML = "";

    const progress = html`&lt;div class="quiz-progress"&gt;
      &lt;span&gt;Question ${state.index + 1} of ${state.total}&lt;/span&gt;
      &lt;span&gt;Score: ${state.score}/${state.total}&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;`;
    const graph = drawGraph(question);
    const prompt = html`&lt;p class="quiz-prompt"&gt;Select an expression.&lt;/p&gt;`;
    const feedback = html`&lt;p class="quiz-feedback" aria-live="polite"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;`;
    const next = html`&lt;button type="button" disabled&gt;Next question&lt;/button&gt;`;
    const options = radioList(question.options, option =&gt; {
      if (state.answered) return;

      state.answered = true;
      const correct = option.id === question.answer.id;
      if (correct) state.score += 1;

      feedback.className = correct
        ? "quiz-feedback correct"
        : "quiz-feedback wrong";
      feedback.innerHTML = correct
        ? "Correct."
        : `Not quite. The answer is &lt;code&gt;${question.answer.label}&lt;/code&gt;.`;

      for (const input of options.querySelectorAll("input")) {
        input.disabled = true;
      }

      next.disabled = false;
      progress.lastElementChild.textContent = `Score: ${state.score}/${state.total}`;
    });

    next.addEventListener("click", () =&gt; {
      state.index += 1;
      if (state.index &lt; state.total) {
        startQuestion();
      } else {
        renderComplete();
      }
    });

    root.append(progress, graph, prompt, feedback, options, next);
  }

  function renderComplete() {
    root.innerHTML = "";

    const summary = html`&lt;div class="quiz-complete"&gt;
      &lt;h3&gt;Quiz complete&lt;/h3&gt;
      &lt;p&gt;Final score: ${state.score}/${state.total}&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;`;
    const restart = html`&lt;button type="button"&gt;Start another quiz&lt;/button&gt;`;
    restart.addEventListener("click", renderStart);

    root.append(summary, restart);
  }
}







function makeQuestion() {
  const answer = randomExpression();
  const options = new Map([[answer.id, answer]]);

  while (options.size &lt; 4) {
    const option = randomExpression();
    options.set(option.id, option);
  }

  return {
    answer,
    options: shuffle(Array.from(options.values()))
  };
}







function randomExpression() {
  const kind = choice(["linear", "quadratic", "cubic", "sine", "cosine"]);

  if (kind === "linear") {
    const m = nonzeroInt(-4, 4);
    const b = int(-6, 6);
    return expression(
      `${formatCoeff(m)}x ${formatSigned(b)}`,
      x =&gt; m * x + b
    );
  }

  if (kind === "quadratic") {
    const a = nonzeroInt(-3, 3);
    const b = int(-5, 5);
    const c = int(-6, 6);
    return expression(
      `${formatCoeff(a)}x² ${formatSignedTerm(b, "x")} ${formatSigned(c)}`,
      x =&gt; a * x * x + b * x + c
    );
  }

  if (kind === "cubic") {
    const a = nonzeroInt(-2, 2);
    const b = int(-3, 3);
    const c = int(-4, 4);
    return expression(
      `${formatCoeff(a)}x³ ${formatSignedTerm(b, "x")} ${formatSigned(c)}`,
      x =&gt; a * x * x * x + b * x + c
    );
  }

  if (kind === "sine") {
    const a = nonzeroInt(-4, 4);
    const k = nonzeroInt(1, 4);
    return expression(`${formatCoeff(a)}sin(${k}x)`, x =&gt; a * Math.sin(k * x));
  }

  const a = nonzeroInt(-4, 4);
  const k = nonzeroInt(1, 4);
  return expression(`${formatCoeff(a)}cos(${k}x)`, x =&gt; a * Math.cos(k * x));
}







function expression(label, evaluate) {
  return {
    id: label.replace(/\s+/g, ""),
    label,
    evaluate,
    toString: () =&gt; label
  };
}







function radioList(options, onSelect) {
  const form = html`&lt;form class="quiz-options" role="radiogroup" aria-label="Expression options"&gt;&lt;/form&gt;`;
  form.value = null;

  for (const option of options) {
    const input = html`&lt;input type="radio" name="quiz-answer"&gt;`;
    const label = html`&lt;label class="quiz-option"&gt;${input}&lt;span&gt;${option.label}&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/label&gt;`;

    input.addEventListener("change", () =&gt; {
      form.value = option;
      form.dispatchEvent(new Event("input", { bubbles: true }));
      onSelect(option);
    });

    form.append(label);
  }

  return form;
}







function drawGraph(question) {
  const width = 720;
  const height = 360;
  const margin = { top: 24, right: 24, bottom: 36, left: 46 };
  const xs = Array.from({ length: 401 }, (_, i) =&gt; -10 + i * 20 / 400);
  const points = xs
    .map(x =&gt; ({ x, y: question.answer.evaluate(x) }))
    .filter(d =&gt; Number.isFinite(d.y));

  const yValues = points.map(d =&gt; d.y).sort((a, b) =&gt; a - b);
  const low = Math.min(quantile(yValues, 0.02), -5);
  const high = Math.max(quantile(yValues, 0.98), 5);
  const yPadding = Math.max((high - low) * 0.08, 1);

  const xScale = d3.scaleLinear()
    .domain([-10, 10])
    .range([margin.left, width - margin.right]);
  const yScale = d3.scaleLinear()
    .domain([low - yPadding, high + yPadding])
    .range([height - margin.bottom, margin.top]);

  const line = d3.line()
    .x(d =&gt; xScale(d.x))
    .y(d =&gt; yScale(d.y));

  const svg = d3.create("svg")
    .attr("viewBox", [0, 0, width, height])
    .attr("role", "img")
    .attr("aria-label", "Graph of an algebraic expression")
    .attr("class", "quiz-graph");

  svg.append("g")
    .attr("transform", `translate(0,${yScale(0)})`)
    .call(d3.axisBottom(xScale).ticks(10));

  svg.append("g")
    .attr("transform", `translate(${xScale(0)},0)`)
    .call(d3.axisLeft(yScale).ticks(8));

  svg.append("g")
    .attr("class", "quiz-grid")
    .call(d3.axisLeft(yScale).ticks(8).tickSize(-(width - margin.left - margin.right)).tickFormat(""));

  svg.append("path")
    .datum(points)
    .attr("fill", "none")
    .attr("stroke", "#1a73e8")
    .attr("stroke-width", 3)
    .attr("d", line);

  return svg.node();
}







function choice(values) {
  return values[Math.floor(Math.random() * values.length)];
}

function int(min, max) {
  return Math.floor(Math.random() * (max - min + 1)) + min;
}

function nonzeroInt(min, max) {
  let value = 0;
  while (value === 0) value = int(min, max);
  return value;
}

function shuffle(values) {
  const copy = values.slice();
  for (let i = copy.length - 1; i &gt; 0; i -= 1) {
    const j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
    [copy[i], copy[j]] = [copy[j], copy[i]];
  }
  return copy;
}

function quantile(sortedValues, p) {
  const index = Math.min(
    sortedValues.length - 1,
    Math.max(0, Math.floor(sortedValues.length * p))
  );
  return sortedValues[index];
}





































function formatCoeff(value) {
  if (value === 1) return "";
  if (value === -1) return "-";
  return `${value}`;
}

function formatSigned(value) {
  if (value === 0) return "+ 0";
  return value &gt; 0 ? `+ ${value}` : `- ${Math.abs(value)}`;
}

function formatSignedTerm(value, symbol) {
  if (value === 0) return "+ 0";
  const magnitude = Math.abs(value);
  const coeff = magnitude === 1 ? "" : `${magnitude}`;
  return value &gt; 0 ? `+ ${coeff}${symbol}` : `- ${coeff}${symbol}`;
}

What this path prepares you to do
By the end of this Algebra path, you should be able to:

manipulate expressions without losing domain restrictions;
solve equations and inequalities and interpret their solution sets;
read and produce graphs from formulas;
recognize how parameters change the shape of a function;
factor, expand, and analyze polynomial expressions;
work with rational, radical, exponential, and logarithmic functions;
solve and graph systems of equations;
translate word problems and data patterns into algebraic models;
use SymPy responsibly to check work, generate examples, and explore patterns.

After this lesson you should be able to:

describe vertical and horizontal shifts, stretches, compressions, and reflections;
interpret parameters in a*f(b*(x-h)) + k;
compute sums, differences, products, quotients, and compositions of functions;
track domain restrictions under operations and composition;
explain what an inverse function does and when it exists.

The transformation template
A useful general template is:
g(x) = a*f(b*(x - h)) + k
where:

a vertically stretches/compresses and may reflect across the x-axis;
b horizontally compresses/stretches and may reflect across the y-axis;
h shifts the graph horizontally;
k shifts the graph vertically.







WarningHorizontal transformations feel backward



The expression f(x - 3) shifts the graph right by 3, not left. The input must be 3 units larger before the base function sees the same internal value.
